9":"1409","1470":"1470","1429":"1429","1390":"1390","25 April 1412":"25 April 1412","Wyck Rissington, Gloucestershire, England":"Wyck Rissington, Gloucestershire, England","Lea Hall, Lancashire, England":"Lea Hall, Lancashire, England","Hoghton, Lancashire, England":"Hoghton, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bothe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Detlef, Manfred, Wolfgang.","North German and Dutch: from the North German personal name <i>Bodo</i> (see   Bode   2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bode","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Otto, Gerd, Gerhard, Helmut, Armin, Dieter, Erna, Ewald, Friedhelm, Fritz, Gunter.","Dutch and German: occupational name for a messenger or representative, Dutch <i>bode</i>, Middle Low German <i>bode</i>. A <i>bode</i> was a medieval official with a variety of different functions.","German and Danish: from the North German personal name <i>Bodo</i>, a derivative of Old Saxon <i>bodo</i> ‘messenger, leader’."]},{"name":"Bottemiller","meanings":["Americanized form of a German surname, probably North German <b>Bottemöller</b>, of which the second element (Middle Low German <i>möller</i>) means ‘miller’ and the first one is perhaps a variant of the personal name   Bothe  . The surname <i>Bottemöller</i> is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Both","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Johann, Otto, Ulrich, Wilhelm.","North German and Dutch: variant of   Bothe  .","Hungarian: variant of <b>Bot</b>, from the old personal name <i>Bot</i> or from the vocabulary word <i>bot</i> ‘stick’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for a shepherd or a village guard. This surname is also found in Slovakia."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":42,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sarah De Bothe was born on 25 April 1412, in Wyck Rissington, Gloucestershire, England as the dau